# 🔖 Project Documentation: Uk_Traffic_Data_Analysis

---

| **Section**                   | **Content**                                                                                                           |
|-------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| 📝 **Project Title**          | **UK_Traffic_Analysis**                                                                                   |
| 🎯 **Objective**              | Analyze vehicle traffic trends across UK regions (2000–2024) using interactive visualizations and descriptive analytics. |
| 📦 **Tech Stack**             | Python, Pandas, Plotly, Streamlit, Matplotlib, Seaborn                                                               |
| 📊 **Dataset Used**           | UK Government Open Data Portal ([UK DfT Statistics](https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets))            |
| 🧠 **Methodology / Workflow** | • Data Collection → Cleaning → EDA → Insight Generation → Streamlit Dashboard                                        |
| 📈 **Models Used**            | ❌ No ML or forecasting models used — project is based on exploratory & visual analytics only                        |
| 📌 **Features**               | • Multi-page Streamlit app<br>• Interactive line, bar, and pie charts<br>• Regional & vehicle-type filters<br>• Dashboard UI |
| 🔍 **Exploratory Analysis**   | • Steady traffic growth (2000–2018)<br>• Sharp drop in 2020 (COVID impact)<br>• Recovery trend in 2024<br>• London as a standout region |
| 📉 **Model Output**           | _Not applicable — visual analysis only_                                                                              |
| 🧪 **Testing**                | Manual validation of data loading, aggregation, and dynamic chart rendering                                           |
| 🌐 **Web App UI (if any)**    | Built with **Streamlit**:<br>• Tabbed interface<br>• Section-based navigation (EDA, Trends, Conclusion)<br>• Responsive layout |




